A064001.name: Odd abundant numbers not divisible by 5.

A064002.name: List pairs (i,j) with 1 <= i <= j in lexicographic order: (1,1), (1,2), (2,2), (1,3), (2,3), (3,3), (1,4), ... Let a(1) = 1. Then for n>=2 if the (n-1)-st pair is (i,j) then a(n) = a(i) + a(j) + 1.

A064003.name: Numbers k such that product of decimal digits = sum of binary digits.

A064004.name: At step n in computing A064413, sequence gives smallest multiple of 2 not yet seen, divided by 2.

A064007.name: At step n in computing A064413, sequence gives smallest multiple of 3 not yet seen, divided by 3.

A064009.name: a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} d(k)*prime(k), where d(k) = A001223.

A064010.name: Numbers k such that sopf(k) = d(k) where d(k) = A001223(k) and sopf(k) = A008472(k).

A064011.name: Sum of distinct primes dividing n! + 1.

A064012.name: usigma(usigma(n))=3*n where usigma(n) is the sum of unitary divisors of n (A034448).

A064013.name: Sum of first n^2 odd primes (=S) is divisible by n and S/n = n mod 2.

A064014.name: Squares with an even number of digits, the respective halves of which are consecutive integers.

A064015.name: Numbers k such that sopf(k)*nud(k) = pi(k), where sopf(k)=A008472, nud(k)=A034444 and pi(k)=A000720.

A064016.name: a(n) = Sum_{k <= 10^n} cototient(k), where cototient is A051953.

A064017.name: Number of ternary trees (A001764) with n nodes and maximal diameter.

A064018.name: a(n) = A002088(10^n) = Sum_{k <= 10^n} phi(k), sum of the Euler totients phi = A000010.

A064019.name: Numbers k such that sopf(k) = sopf(k^2 - 1), where sopf(k) = A008472(k).

A064020.name: Numbers n such that sf(n) = phi(n), where sf(n) = A013928(n).

A064021.name: Squares k^2 such that reverse(k)^2 = reverse(k^2), excluding squares of palindromes.
formula: {n = A000290(k) such that A004086(A000290(k)) = A000290(A004086(k)) and k is not in A002113}. - _Jonathan Vos Post_, May 02 2011

A064022.name: a(n) is the smallest value of m such that prod(m) = n*length(m)*sum(m) where prod(m) is the product of the digits of m, length(m) is the number of digits of m, sum(m) is the sum of the digits of m; or 0 if no such m exists.

A064023.name: a(n) is the smallest prime m such that prod(m) = n*length(m)*sum(m) where prod(m) is the product of the digits of m, length(m) is the number of digits of m, sum(m) is the sum of the digits of m; or 0 if no such m exists.

A064024.name: a(n) = value of k such that absolute difference of 2^n and 3^k is minimized.

A064025.name: Length of period of the continued fraction for sqrt(n!).

A064026.name: Numbers n such that d(n) + d(n+1) + d(n+2) = 8, where d(n) = A001223.

A064027.name: a(n) = (-1)^n*Sum_{d|n} (-1)^d*d^2.
formula: Logarithmic derivative of A224364. - _Paul D. Hanna_, Apr 04 2013
Bisection: a(2*k-1) = A001157(2*k-1), a(2*k) = 4*A001157(k) - A050999(2*k), k >= 1. In the Hardy reference a(n) = sigma^*_2(n). - _Wolfdieter Lang_, Jan 07 2017
Conjecture: Sum_{k=1..n} a(k) ~ 7 * Zeta(3) * n^3 / 24. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Nov 10 2018

A064028.name: Sum of the unitary divisors of n!.

A064029.name: Numbers k such that sopfr(k) = ud(k), where sopfr = A001414 and ud = A034444.

A064030.name: Product of unitary divisors of n!.

A064031.name: Product of non-unitary divisors of n!.

A064032.name: Product of unitary divisors of central binomial coefficients.

A064033.name: Product of non-unitary divisors of central binomial coefficients or a(n)=1 if all divisors are unitary. See A046098.

A064034.name: 2-dimensional table T(i, j) defined for any integers i and j, read by antidiagonals in the southeast quadrant. T(i, j) gives the "Fibonacci depth" of (i, j): form the Fibonacci sequence starting with i, j: w(0) = i, w(1) = j, w(n) = w(n-1) + w(n-2). It can be shown that for all but finitely many n, the w(n) have the same sign, i.e., are all positive, all negative or all zero. T(i, j), is the smallest number of iterations required to find out which of these cases holds.

A064036.name: Number of walks of length n on cubic lattice, starting at origin, staying in first (nonnegative) octant.

A064037.name: Number of walks of length 2n on cubic lattice, starting and finishing at origin and staying in first (nonnegative) octant.
formula: G.f. is a large expression in terms of hypergeometric functions and sqrt's, see Maple program.  - _Mark van Hoeij_, Apr 19 2013

A064038.name: Numerator of average number of swaps needed to bubble sort a string of n distinct letters.
formula: a(n) = numerator of sum(k=0..n-1, k/2). - _Arkadiusz Wesolowski_, Aug 09 2012
a(n) = n*(n+1)*(3-i^(n*(n+1)))/8, where i=sqrt(-1). - _Bruno Berselli_, Oct 01 2012

A064039.name: Reversed inversion vectors for the permutations of A060117, presented as pseudo-decimal numbers.

A064040.name: Number of distinct prime divisors of n is a prime.

A064042.name: At step n in computing A064413, sequence gives smallest multiple of 5 not yet seen, divided by 5.

A064043.name: Number of length 3 walks on an n-dimensional hypercubic lattice starting at the origin and staying in the nonnegative part.

A064044.name: Square array read by antidiagonals of number of length k walks on an n-dimensional hypercubic lattice starting at the origin and staying in the nonnegative part.
formula: a(n,k) = Sum{j=0..k} C(k,j) B(j) a(n-1,k-j) where B(j) = C(j,[j/2]) = A001405(j) with a(0,0) = 1 and a(0,k) = 0 for k>0.
E.g.f: 1/(1 - x*besseli(0, 2*y) - x*y*besseli(1, 2*y)). - _Paul D. Hanna_, Apr 07 2005

A064045.name: Square array read by antidiagonals of number of length 2k walks on an n-dimensional hypercubic lattice starting and finishing at the origin and staying in the nonnegative part.
formula: a(n,k) = Sum_{j=0..k} C(2k,2j) c(j) a(n-1,k-j) where c(j) = C(2j,j)/(j+1) = A000108(j) with a(0,0) = 1 and a(0,k) = 0 for k>0.

A064046.name: Number of length 6 walks on an n-dimensional hypercubic lattice starting and finishing at the origin and staying in the nonnegative part.

A064047.name: Number of numbers only appearing once in 1-to-n multiplication table.

A064048.name: Number of most frequently occurring numbers in the 1-to-n multiplication table.

A064049.name: Number of possible arrangements of numbers 1 to n*(n+1)/2 in a triangle of n rows so that each row and each diagonal is increasing or decreasing.

A064050.name: Number of essentially different (not mappable to each other by reflection or rotation) arrangements of numbers 1 to n*(n+1)/2 in a triangle of n rows, in such a way that each row and each diagonal is increasing or decreasing.

A064052.name: Not sqrt(n)-smooth: some prime factor of n is > sqrt(n).

A064053.name: Dragonette's sequence gamma(n).
formula: Convolution of this sequence and A000041 is A000025. - _Michael Somos_, Jun 19 2003

A064054.name: Tenth column of trinomial coefficients.
formula: G.f.: (1+x-x^2)*(5-5*x+x^2)/(1-x)^10, numerator polynomial is N3(9, x)= 5+0*x-9*x^2+6*x^3-x^4 from array A063420.
a(n) = A111808(n+5,9) for n>3. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Aug 17 2005
a(n) = 5*binomial(n+5,5) + 20*binomial(n+5,6) + 21*binomial(n+5,7) + 8*binomial(n+5,8) + binomial(n+5,9) (see our comment in A026729). - _Vladimir Shevelev_ and _Peter J. C. Moses_, Jun 22 2012
a(n) = GegenbauerC(N, -n, -1/2) where N = 9 if 9<n else 2*n-9. - _Peter Luschny_, May 10 2016

A064055.name: Ninth column of quadrinomial coefficients.
formula: G.f.: (3+4*x-16*x^2+15*x^3-6*x^4+x^5 )/(1-x)^9, numerator polynomial is N4(8, x) from the array A063421.
a(n) = 3*C(n+3,3) + 19*C(n+3,4) + 30*C(n+3,5) + 21*C(n+3,6) + 7*C(n+3,7) + C(n+3,8) (see comment in A071675). - _Vladimir Shevelev_ and _Peter J. C. Moses_, Jun 22 2012

A064056.name: Seventh column of quintinomial coefficients.
formula: G.f.: (3-2*x-2*x^2+3*x^3-x^4)/(1-x)^7; numerator polynomial is N5(6, x) from the array A063422.
a(n) = 3*C(n+2,2) + 10*C(n+2,3) + 10*C(n+2,4) + 5*C(n+2,5) + C(n+2,6) (see comment in A213887). - _Vladimir Shevelev_ and _Peter J. C. Moses_, Jun 22 2012

A064057.name: Eighth column of quintinomial coefficients.
formula: G.f.: (2+2*x-8*x^2+7*x^3-2*x^4 )/(1-x)^8; numerator polynomial is N5(7, x) from the array A063422.
a(n) = 2*C(n+2,2) + 12*C(n+2,3) + 20*C(n+2,4) + 15*C(n+2,5) + 6*C(n+2,6) + C(n+2,7) (see comment in A213887). - _Vladimir Shevelev_ and _Peter J. C. Moses_, Jun 22 2012

A064058.name: Ninth column of quintinomial coefficients.
formula: G.f.: (1+6*x-14*x^2+11*x^3-3*x^4)/(1-x)^9; numerator polynomial is N5(8, x) from the array A063422.
a(n) = C(n+2,2) + 12*C(n+2,3) + 31*C(n+2,4) + 35*C(n+2,5) + 21*C(n+2,6) + 7*C(n+2,7) + C(n+2,8) (see comment in A213887). - _Vladimir Shevelev_ and _Peter J. C. Moses_, Jun 22 2012

A064059.name: Seventh column of Catalan triangle A009766.
formula: a(n) = binomial(n+1,6)-2*binomial(n,5), for n>=12. - _Zerinvary Lajos_, Jul 19 2006

A064060.name: Number of connected, homeomorphically irreducible (also called series-reduced) trees with n >= 2 labeled leaves (numbers in nondecreasing order).

A064061.name: Eighth column of Catalan triangle A009766.

A064062.name: Generalized Catalan numbers C(2; n).
formula: G.f.: (1 + 2*x*C(2*x)) / (1+x) = 1/(1 - x*C(2*x)) with C(x) g.f. of Catalan numbers A000108.
a(n) = Sum{ k= 0...n, A059365(n, k)*2^(n-k) }. - _Philippe Deléham_, Jan 19 2004
a(n) = the upper left term in M^n, M = the production matrix:

- _Gary W. Adamson_, Jul 08 2011 D-finite with recurrence: n*a(n) +(12-7n)*a(n-1)+4*(3-2n)*a(n-2)=0. - _R. J. Mathar_, Nov 16 2011 (This follows easily from the generating function. - _Robert Israel_, Nov 30 2014)
G.f. satisfies: A(x) = 1 + A(x)^4 * Integral 1/A(x)^2 dx. - _Paul D. Hanna_, Dec 24 2013
G.f. satisfies: Integral 1/A(x)^2 dx = x - x^2*G(x), where G(x) is the o.g.f. of A000257, the number of rooted bicubic maps. - _Paul D. Hanna_, Dec 24 2013
G.f. A(x) satisfies: A(x - 2*x^2) = 1/(1-x). - _Paul D. Hanna_, Nov 30 2014
a(n) = hypergeometric([1-n, n], [-n], 2) for n > 0. - _Peter Luschny_, Nov 30 2014
O.g.f. A(x) =  1 + series reversion of (x*(1 - x)/(1 + x)^2). Logarithmically differentiating (A(x) - 1)/x gives 3 + 17*x + 111*x^2 + ..., essentially a g.f for A119259. - _Peter Bala_, Oct 01 2015

A064063.name: Generalized Catalan numbers C(3; n).
formula: G.f.: (1+3*x*c(3*x)/2)/(1+x/2) = 1/(1-x*c(3*x)) with c(x) g.f. of Catalan numbers A000108.
a(n) = Sum_{ k=0..n} A059365(n, k)*3^(n-k). - _Philippe Deléham_, Jan 19 2004

Given the semi-axes a,b of an ellipse, then Ramanujan gave the highly accurate formula for the perimeter p = Pi((a+b) + (3(a-b)^2)/(10(a+b) + sqrt(a^2 + 14ab + b^2))). If we let h = ((a-b)/(a+b))^2, then (p/(Pi(a+b))-1)/4 = (3/4)* h/(10 + sqrt(4 - 3*h)) = 1*(h/16) + 1*(h/16)^2 + 4*(h/16)^3 + 25*(h/16)^4 + ... . - _Michael Somos_, Apr 11 2007
a(n) = upper left term in M^n, M = the infinite square production matrix:
D-finite with recurrence: 2*n*a(n) + (-23*n+36)*a(n-1) + 6*(-2*n+3)*a(n-2) = 0. - _R. J. Mathar_, Dec 03 2012 (Formula verified and used for computations. - _Fung Lam_, Mar 05 2014)
a(n) = hypergeometric([1-n, n], [-n], 3) for n>0. - _Peter Luschny_, Nov 30 2014

A064064.name: n-th step is to add a(n) to each previous number a(k) (including itself, i.e., k <= n) to produce n+1 more terms of the sequence, starting with a(0)=1.
formula: a(0) = 1 and a(n+1) = a(A002262(n)) + a(A003056(n)) for any n >= 0. - _Rémy Sigrist_, Aug 07 2017

A064065.name: n-th step is to add a(n) to each previous number a(k) (excluding itself, i.e., k < n) to produce n more terms of the sequence, starting with a(0)=0, a(1)=1.

A064066.name: n-th step is to add a(n) to each previous number a(k) (excluding itself, i.e., k < n) to produce n more terms of the sequence, starting with a(0)=1, a(1)=1.

A064067.name: n-th step is to add a(n) to each previous number a(k) (excluding itself, i.e., k < n) to produce n more terms of the sequence, starting with a(0)=1, a(1)=2.

A064076.name: Lesser of odd twin prime powers (greater = A064077).

A064077.name: Greater of odd twin prime powers (lesser = A064076).

A064078.name: Zsigmondy numbers for a = 2, b = 1: Zs(n, 2, 1) is the greatest divisor of 2^n - 1 (A000225) that is coprime to 2^m - 1 for all positive integers m < n.
formula: Denominator of Sum_{d|n} d*moebius(n/d)/(2^d-1). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Apr 02 2004
a(n) = A019320(n)/(A019320(n) mod n) for n > 1. - _Thomas Ordowski_, Oct 24 2017

A064079.name: Zsigmondy numbers for a = 3, b = 1: Zs(n, 3, 1) is the greatest divisor of 3^n - 1^n (A024023) that is relatively prime to 3^m - 1^m for all positive integers m < n.

A064080.name: Zsigmondy numbers for a = 4, b = 1: Zs(n, 4, 1) is the greatest divisor of 4^n - 1^n (A024036) that is relatively prime to 4^m - 1^m for all positive integers m < n.

A064081.name: Zsigmondy numbers for a = 5, b = 1: Zs(n, 5, 1) is the greatest divisor of 5^n - 1^n (A024049) that is relatively prime to 5^m - 1^m for all positive integers m < n.

A064082.name: Zsigmondy numbers for a = 6, b = 1: Zs(n, 6, 1) is the greatest divisor of 6^n - 1^n (A024062) that is relatively prime to 6^m - 1^m for all positive integers m < n.

A064083.name: Zsigmondy numbers for a = 7, b = 1: Zs(n, 7, 1) is the greatest divisor of 7^n - 1^n (A024075) that is relatively prime to 7^m - 1^m for all positive integers m < n.

A064084.name: A multiplicative version of 2^n - 1 (A000225).
formula: a(n) = (2^((p_1)^(e_1)) - 1) * ... * (2^((p_k)^(e_k)) - 1) where (p_1)^(e_1) * ... * (p_k)^(e_k) is the prime factorization of n.

A064086.name: Condensed version of A064085: all terms of A064085 with values greater than 1 (which coincides with all terms of A064085 with nonprime power index).

A064087.name: Generalized Catalan numbers C(4; n).
formula: G.f.: (1+4*x*c(4*x)/3)/(1+x/3) = 1/(1-x*c(4*x)) with c(x) g.f. of Catalan numbers A000108.
a(n) = Sum_{k=0...n} A059365(n, k)*4^(n-k). - _Philippe Deléham_, Jan 19 2004
a(n) = hypergeometric([1-n, n], [-n], 4) for n > 0. - _Peter Luschny_, Nov 30 2014

A064088.name: Generalized Catalan numbers C(5; n).
formula: G.f.: (1+5*x*c(5*x)/4)/(1+x/4) = 1/(1-x*c(5*x)) with c(x) g.f. of Catalan numbers A000108.
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} A059365(n, k)*5^(n-k). - _Philippe Deléham_, Jan 19 2004
a(n) = upper left term in M^n, M = an infinite square production matrix as follows:

A064089.name: Generalized Catalan numbers C(6; n).
formula: G.f.: (1 + 6*x*c(6*x)/5)/(1+x/5) = 1/(1 - x*c(6*x)) with c(x) g.f. of Catalan numbers A000108.
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} A059365(n, k)*6^(n-k). - _Philippe Deléham_, Jan 19 2004

A064090.name: Generalized Catalan numbers C(7; n).
formula: G.f.: (1+7*x*c(7*x)/6)/(1+x/6) = 1/(1-x*c(7*x)) with c(x) g.f. of Catalan numbers A000108.
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} A059365(n, k)*7^(n-k). - _Philippe Deléham_, Jan 19 2004

A064091.name: Generalized Catalan numbers C(8; n).
formula: G.f.: (1 + 8*x*c(8*x)/7)/(1+x/7) = 1/(1 - x*c(8*x)) with c(x) g.f. of Catalan numbers A000108.
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} A059365(n, k)*8^(n-k). - _Philippe Deléham_, Jan 19 2004

A064092.name: Generalized Catalan numbers C(9; n).
formula: G.f.: (1 + 9*x*c(9*x)/8)/(1+x/8) = 1/(1 - x*c(9*x)) with c(x) g.f. of Catalan numbers A000108.
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} A059365(n, k)*9^(n-k). - _Philippe Deléham_, Jan 19 2004

A064093.name: Generalized Catalan numbers C(10; n).
formula: G.f.: (1 + 10*x*c(10*x)/9)/(1+x/9) = 1/(1 - x*c(10*x)) with c(x) g.f. of Catalan numbers A000108.
a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} A059365(n, k)*10^(n-k). - _Philippe Deléham_, Jan 19 2004

A064094.name: Triangle composed of generalized Catalan numbers.
formula: G.f. for column m: (x^m)/(1-x*c(m*x))= (x^m)*((m-1)+m*x*c(m*x))/(m-1+x) with the g.f. c(x) of Catalan numbers A000108.

A064096.name: Fifth diagonal of triangle A064094.
formula: a(n)= 1+3*n+5*n^2+5*n^3. Fourth row polynomial (n=3) of Catalan triangle A009766.

A064097.name: A quasi-logarithm defined inductively by a(1) = 0 and a(p) = 1 + a(p-1) if p is prime and a(n*m) = a(n) + a(m) if m,n > 1.
formula: Conjectures: for n>1, log(n) < a(n) < (5/2)*log(n); lim n ->infinity sum(k=1, n, a(k))/(n*log(n)-n) = C = 1.8(4)... - _Benoit Cloitre_, Oct 30 2002
Conjecture: for n>1, floor(log_2(n)) <= a(n) < (5/2)*log(n). - _Robert G. Wilson v_, Aug 10 2013
a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} a(p_k)*e_k if n is composite with factorization p_1^e_1 * ... * p_k^e_k. - _Orson R. L. Peters_, May 10 2016
a(1) = 0; for n > 1, a(n) = 1 + a(A060681(n)). [From _Jaroslav Krizek_'s Jan 28 2010 formula in comments.]

A064098.name: a(n+1) = (a(n)^2 + a(n-1)^2)/a(n-2), with a(1) = a(2) = a(3) = 1.
formula: Conjecture: lim_{n -> infinity} log(log(a(n)))/n exists = 0.48.... - _Benoit Cloitre_, Aug 07 2002. This is true - see below.

For this subsequence of the Markoff numbers, we have 2^(F(n-1) - 1) < a(n) < 3^(F(n-1) - 1) for n > 4, where F(n) are the Fibonacci numbers with F(0)=0, F(1)=1, F(n+1) = F(n) + F(n-1). Hence log(log(a(n)))/n tends to log((1 + sqrt(5))/2) as previously conjectured. - _Andrew Hone_, Jan 16 2006
a(n) = 3 * a(n-1) * a(n-2) - a(n-3). a(4-n) = a(n) for all n in Z. - _Michael Somos_, Jan 12 2013

A064101.name: Primes p = p(k) such that p(k) + p(k+5) = p(k+1) + p(k+4) = p(k+2) + p(k+3).

A064102.name: Primes p = p(k) such that p(k) + p(k+7) = p(k+1) + p(k+6) = p(k+2) + p(k+5) = p(k+3) + p(k+4).

A064105.name: 2nd column of 3rd-order Zeckendorf array.
formula: Any number n has a unique representation as a sum of terms from {2, 3, 4, 6, 9, 13, 19, ...} (cf. A000930) such that no two terms are adjacent or pen-adjacent; e.g. 8=6+2. Sequence gives all n where that representation involves 2.

A064106.name: 3rd column of 3rd-order Zeckendorf array.
formula: Any number n has a unique representation as a sum of terms from {3, 4, 6, 9, 13, 19, ...} (cf. A000930) such that no two terms are adjacent or pen-adjacent; e.g. 12=9+3. Sequence gives all n where that representation involves 3.

A064119.name: Numbers k such that the first k digits of the Golden Ratio form a prime.

A064125.name: Numbers k such that k and k+1 have the same sum of unitary divisors (A034448).

A064126.name: Number of divisors of 10^n - 1 that are relatively prime to 10^m - 1 for all 0 < m < n.

A064127.name: Number of divisors of 11^n - 1 that are relatively prime to 11^m - 1 for all 0 < m < n.

a(n) = F(2*n - 3)*F(2*n - 5) = 1 + F(2*(n - 2))^2, for n >= 2, with F(-1) = 1. See the W. Lang comments above. - _Wolfdieter Lang_, May 26 2020

Column k has e.g.f. exp(x)*(BesselI(k,2*x)-BesselI(k+2,2*x)). - _Paul Barry_, Feb 16 2006

n-th row is generated from M^n * V, where M = the infinite tridiagonal matrix with all 1's in the super, main and subdiagonals; and V = the infinite vector [1,0,0,0,...]. E.g., Row 3 = (4, 5, 3, 1), since M^3 * V = [4, 5, 3, 1, 0, 0, 0, ...]. - _Gary W. Adamson_, Nov 04 2006
G.f.: 2 / (1 - x + sqrt(1 - 2*x - 3*x^2) - 2*x*y) = Sum_{n >= k >= 0} T(n, k) * x^n * y^k. - _Michael Somos_, Jun 06 2016

formula: a(n, m)=sum(A009766(n, k)*A008277(k, m), k=m..n), n >= m >= 1 else 0. Product of Catalan triangular matrix (without row n=0 and column m=0) with Stirling2 triangular matrix.

A064310.name: Generalized Catalan numbers C(-1; n).
formula: G.f.: (1+x*c(-x)/2)/(1-x/2) = 1/(1-x*c(-x)) with c(x) g.f. of Catalan numbers A000108.

A064311.name: Generalized Catalan numbers C(-2; n).
formula: G.f.: (1+2*x*c(-2*x)/3)/(1-x/3) = 1/(1-x*c(-2*x)) with c(x) g.f. of Catalan numbers A000108.
a(n) = hypergeom([1-n, n], [-n], -2) for n>0. - _Peter Luschny_, Nov 30 2014

A064312.name: a(n) = B(n)*P(n), where B(n) are Bell numbers (A000110) and P(n) are numbers of arrangements of a set of n elements (A000522).
formula: Integral representation as n-th moment of a positive function on a positive half-axis, in Maple notation: a(n)= int(x^n*sum(exp(-x/k)*Heaviside(x-k)/(k*k!), k=1..infinity), x=0..infinity).
E.g.f.: A(x) = Sum_{n>=0} exp(n*x-1)/(n!*(1-n*x)). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Feb 04 2008

A064313.name: Integer part of area of a regular polygon with n sides each of length 1.

A064314.name: Total length of longest increasing runs in all permutations of n elements.

A064315.name: Triangle of number of permutations by length of shortest ascending run.
formula: Sequence (1, 3, 2, 5, 4) has ascending runs (1, 3), (2, 5), (4), the shortest is length 1. Of all permutations of (1, 2, 3, 4, 5), T(5,1) = 101 have shortest ascending run of length 1.

A064316.name: Total length of shortest ascending runs of permutations of length n.

A064320.name: a(n) = Product_{j=1..n} j^C(n-1,j-1).
formula: Main diagonal of array T(i, 1)=i, T(1, j)=j and T(i, j)=T(i-1, j)*T(i-1, j-1). - _Benoit Cloitre_, Aug 16 2003, corrected Apr 16 2015

A064325.name: Generalized Catalan numbers C(-3; n).
formula: G.f.: (1+3*x*c(-3*x)/4)/(1-x/4) = 1/(1-x*c(-3*x)) with c(x) g.f. of Catalan numbers A000108.
a(n) = hypergeometric([1-n, n], [-n], -3) for n>0. - _Peter Luschny_, Nov 30 2014

A064326.name: Generalized Catalan numbers C(-4; n).
formula: G.f.: (1+4*x*c(-4*x)/5)/(1-x/5) = 1/(1-x*c(-4*x)) with c(x) g.f. of Catalan numbers A000108.
a(n) = hypergeometric([1-n, n], [-n], -4) for n > 0. - _Peter Luschny_, Nov 30 2014

A064327.name: Generalized Catalan numbers C(-5; n).
formula: G.f.: (1+5*x*c(-5*x)/6)/(1-x/6) = 1/(1-x*c(-5*x)) with c(x) g.f. of Catalan numbers A000108.
a(n) = hypergeometric([1-n, n], [-n], -5) for n > 0. - _Peter Luschny_, Nov 30 2014

A064328.name: Generalized Catalan numbers C(-6; n).
formula: G.f.: (1+6*x*c(-6*x)/7)/(1-x/7) = 1/(1-x*c(-6*x)) with c(x) g.f. of Catalan numbers A000108.

A064329.name: Generalized Catalan numbers C(-7; n).
formula: G.f.: (1+7*x*c(-7*x)/8)/(1-x/8) = 1/(1-x*c(-7*x)) with c(x) g.f. of Catalan numbers A000108.

A064330.name: Generalized Catalan numbers C(-8; n).
formula: G.f.: (1+8*x*c(-8*x)/9)/(1-x/9) = 1/(1-x*c(-8*x)) with c(x) g.f. of Catalan numbers A000108.

A064331.name: Generalized Catalan numbers C(-9; n).
formula: G.f.: (1+9*x*c(-9*x)/10)/(1-x/10) = 1/(1-x*c(-9*x)) with c(x) g.f. of Catalan numbers A000108.

A064334.name: Triangle composed of generalized Catalan numbers.
formula: G.f. for column m: (x^m)/(1-x*c(-m*x))= (x^m)*((m+1)+m*x*c(-m*x))/((m+1)-x), m>0, with the g.f. c(x) of Catalan numbers A000108.
T(n, m) = Sum_{k=0..n-m-1} (n-m-k)*binomial(n-m-1+k, k)*(-m)^k/(n-m), with T(n,0) = T(n,n)=1.
T(n, k) = hypergeometric([1-n+k, n-k], [-n+k], -k) if k<n else 1. - _Peter Luschny_, Nov 30 2014

A064335.name: a(n) = 6*(2*n)!/(n+2).
formula: a(n) = Integral_{x=0..oo} (x^n*(exp(-sqrt(x)) * (-1+sqrt(x)+2/sqrt(x)) + x*Ei(-sqrt(x))) ), n=0, 1..., where Ei(y) is the exponential integral. Representation as the n-th moment of a positive function on a positive half-axis, in Maple notation. This representation is unique.

A064336.name: Maximal prime numbers with increasing prime differences.
formula: a(1) = 2, a(n+1) = MAX {prime p | p <= a(n) + p(n)} (where p(n) is the n-th prime number).

A064337.name: Minimal prime numbers with increasing prime differences.
formula: a(1) = 2, a(n+1) = MIN {prime p | p >= a(n) + p(n)} (where p(n) is the n-th prime number).

A064338.name: Row sums of signed triangle A064334.

A064339.name: Row sums of unsigned triangle A064334.

A064348.name: Numbers k such that k and k+1 have the same sum of unitary divisors and the same number of divisors.

A064350.name: a(n) = (3*n)!/n!.
formula: Integral representation as n-th moment of a positive function on a positive half-axis, in Maple notation: a(n)=int(x^n*BesselK(1/3, 2*sqrt(x/27))/(3*Pi*sqrt(x)), x=0..infinity), n=0, 1, ...

A recursive formula: a(n) = (27 * (n - 1)^2 + 27 * (n - 1) + 6) * a(n - 1) with a(0) = 1. An explicit formula following from the recursion equation: a(n) = (3/2)*27^n*GAMMA(n+2/3)*GAMMA(n+1/3)/(Pi*3^(1/2)). - _Thomas Wieder_, Nov 15 2004
E.g.f.: (with interpolated zeros) exp(x^3). - _Geoffrey Critzer_, Dec 30 2012

A064351.name: Numbers n such that n and n+1 have the same sum and number of prime divisors (with repetition).

A064352.name: a(n) = (3*n)!/(2*n)!.
formula: Integral representation as n-th moment of a positive function on a positive half-axis: a(n) = Integral_{x>=0} (x^n*exp(-2*x/27)*(BesselK(1/3, 2*x/27) + BesselK(2/3, 2*x/27))*(sqrt(3)/(27*Pi))).
From Carleman's criterion Sum_{n>=1} a(n)^(-1/(2*n) = infinity the above solution of the Stieltjes moment problem is unique. - _Karol A. Penson_, Jan 13 2018

A064353.name: Kolakoski-(1,3) sequence: the alphabet is {1,3}, and a(n) is the length of the n-th run.

A064354.name: Distinct values arising in the sequence of the least common multiples of the first n composite numbers.

A064355.name: Number of subsets of {1,2,..n} that sum to 1 mod n.
formula: a(n) = 1/n * sum_{d divides n and d is odd} 2^(n/d) * mu(d); (mu(d) is the Moebius function, sequence A008683).

A064356.name: Dimension of J_(12n,n+1), the Jacobi form of weight 12n and index n+1.

A064357.name: Inverse of sequence A035506 considered as a permutation of the natural numbers.

A064358.name: Inverse of sequence A052330 considered as a permutation of the natural numbers.

A064359.name: Inverse of sequence A052331 considered as a permutation of the natural numbers.

A064360.name: Inverse of sequence A029654 considered as a permutation of the natural numbers.

A064361.name: Numbers k such that prime(k)^2 + k is prime.

A064362.name: Numbers n such that no Lucas number is a multiple of n.

A064363.name: Number of 2 X 2 regular integer matrices with elements from {0,...,n} up to row and column permutation.

A064364.name: Positive integers sorted by A001414(n), the sum of their prime divisors, as the major key and n as the minor key.

A064365.name: a(0) = 0; thereafter a(n) = a(n-1)-prime(n) if positive and new, otherwise a(n) = a(n-1)+prime(n), where prime(n) is the n-th prime.

A064366.name: Special binomial coefficient: a(n) = C(sigma(n), phi(n)).
formula: a(n) = C(A000203(n), A000010(n)); at prime indices it gives triangular numbers (A034953(p)).

A064367.name: a(n) = 2^n mod prime(n), or 2^n = k*prime(n) + a(n) with integer k.

A064368.name: Number of 2 X 2 symmetric singular matrices with entries from {0,...,n}.
formula: a(n) = n+1+2*Sum_{k=1..n} Sum_{d^2|k} phi(d), where phi = Euler totient function A000010.

A064369.name: Smallest integer in Recamán's sequence (A005132) to appear n times.

A064370.name: Zero, together with positive numbers k such that the prime(k) - k is a square.

A064371.name: Zero, together with positive numbers n such that the n-th prime + n is a square.

A064372.name: Additive function a(n) defined by the recursive formula a(1)=1 and a(p^k)=a(k) for any prime p.
formula: a(1) = 1, a(n) = sum(k=1..A001221(n), a(A124010(n,k)) ) for n > 1. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Aug 27 2011

A064373.name: "60-60-842", a popular song by the B52's.

A064374.name: Numbers k such that sigma(k) > phi(k)^2.

A064375.name: Numbers n such that sigma_2(n) > phi(n)^3.

A064376.name: Numbers n such that sigma_3(n) > phi(n)^4.

A064377.name: Numbers n such that sigma_4(n) > phi(n)^5.

A064379.name: Triangle whose n-th row is list of numbers that are infinitarily relatively prime to n (n=2,3,..).

A064380.name: Number of numbers that are infinitarily relatively prime to n; the infinitary EulerPhi.
formula: a(n) = Sum{t_1>=0} Sum{t_2>=0}... Sum{t_m>=0} (-1)^(t_1+...+t_m} *floor(n/(q_1^t_1*...*q_m^t_m)), where q_i are distinct terms of A050376, such that n=q_1*...*q_m. - _Vladimir Shevelev_, Apr 17 2010

A064381.name: Number of subsets of {2,...,n} such that the product of their elements is congruent to 0 (mod n+1).

A064382.name: Number of ways to put numbers 1, 2, ..., n*(n+1)/2 in a triangular array of n rows in such a way that each row is increasing or decreasing.

A064383.name: Integers n >= 1 such that n divides 0!-1!+2!-3!+4!-...+(-1)^{n-1}(n-1)!.
formula: Up to n=600000, these are just the divisors of 4*5*13*37*463.

A064384.name: Primes p such that p divides 0!-1!+2!-3!+...+(-1)^{p-1}(p-1)!.

A064387.name: Variation (2) on Recamán's sequence (A005132): to get a(n), we first try to subtract n from a(n-1): a(n) = a(n-1)-n if positive and not already in the sequence; if not then a(n) = a(n-1)+n+i, where i >= 0 is the smallest number such that a(n-1)+n+i has not already appeared.

A064388.name: Variation (3) on Recamán's sequence (A005132): set s (the step size) initially equal to 2; to get a(n), we first try to subtract s from a(n-1): a(n) = a(n-1)-s if positive and not already in the sequence, in which case we change s to s+1; if not, a(n) = a(n-1)+s+i, where i >= 0 is the smallest number such that a(n-1)+s+i has not already appeared and now we change s to s+i+1

A064389.name: Variation (4) on Recamán's sequence (A005132): to get a(n), we first try to subtract n from a(n-1): a(n) = a(n-1)-n if positive and not already in the sequence; if not then we try to add n: a(n) = a(n-1)+n if not already in the sequence; if this fails we try to subtract n+1 from a(n-1), or to add n+1 to a(n-1), or to subtract n+2, or to add n+2, etc., until one of these produces a positive number not already in the sequence - this is a(n).

A064391.name: Triangle T(n,k) with zeroth row {1} and row n for n >= 1 giving number of partitions of n with crank k, for -n <= k <= n.
formula: G.f. for k-th column is Sum(m>=1, (-1)^m*x^(k*m)*(x^((m^2+m)/2)-x^((m^2-m)/2)))/Product(m>=1, 1-x^m). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Dec 22 2004

A064392.name: Numbers in A064383 that are squarefree.

A064393.name: Exponent of highest power of 2 dividing n! equals the largest prime <= n.

A064394.name: Exponent of highest power of 2 dividing n! equals the largest prime < n.

A064395.name: Primes p for which the exponent of the highest power of 2 dividing p! is equal to prevprime(p).

A064396.name: Primes p for which the exponent of the highest power of 2 dividing p! is equal to prevprime(prevprime(p)).

A064397.name: Numbers n such that prime(n) + prime(n+1) is a square.

A064398.name: Numbers n such that p(n) + p(n+1) is a square and n is prime.

A064399.name: Numbers k whose sum of digits exceeds the sum of the digits of k^2.

A064400.name: Number of ordered pairs a,b of elements in the dihedral group D_2n such that the subgroup generated by the pair a,b is the entire group D_2n.

A064401.name: Numbers n such that n! - prime(n) is prime.

A064402.name: Numbers n such that prime(n)+n is a prime, where prime(n) denotes the n-th prime number.

A064403.name: Numbers k such that prime(k) + k and prime(k) - k are both primes.

A064404.name: When the numerator - denominator (A064169) in n-th harmonic number is prime.

A064405.name: Number of even entries (A048967) minus the number of odd entries (A001316) in row n of Pascal's triangle (A007318).
formula: a(n) = sum(k=0, n, (-1)^C(n, k) ); a(2^n) = 2^n-3; a(2^n+1)=2^n-6; more generally there's a sequence z(k) such that for any k>=0 and for 2^n >k, a(2^n+k) = 2^n+z(k); for k=0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8... z(k) = -3, -6, -5, -12, -3, -10, -9, -24, 1, ... - _Benoit Cloitre_, Oct 18 2002
a(2n) = a(n) + n, a(2n+1) = 2a(n). - _Ralf Stephan_, Mar 05 2004
a(n)=-sum{k=0..n, mu(binomial(n, k) mod 2)}; - _Paul Barry_, Apr 29 2005

A064406.name: The accumulation of the number of even entries (A048967) over the number of odd entries (A001316) in row n of Pascal's triangle (A007318).

A064407.name: Even numbers not the sum of a pair of the lesser of the twin primes.

A064408.name: Even numbers not the sum of a pair of the greater of the twin primes.

A064409.name: Even numbers not the sum of a pair twin primes, one the lesser and the other the greater.

A064410.name: Number of partitions of n with zero crank.
formula: a(n) ~ exp(Pi*sqrt(2*n/3)) * Pi / (3 * 2^(9/2) * n^(3/2)). - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, May 06 2018
a(n > 1) = A064428(n) - A001522(n), where A001522/A064428 count odd/even-length compositions with alternating parts strictly decreasing. - _Gus Wiseman_, Apr 02 2021

A064412.name: At stage 1, start with a unit equilateral equiangular triangle. At each successive stage add 3*(n-1) new triangles around outside with edge-to-edge contacts. Sequence gives number of triangles (regardless of size) at n-th stage.

A064413.name: EKG sequence (or ECG sequence): a(1) = 1; a(2) = 2; for n > 2, a(n) = smallest number not already used which shares a factor with a(n-1).
formula: a(n) = smallest number not already used such that gcd(a(n), a(n-1)) > 1.

In Lagarias-Rains-Sloane (2002), it is conjectured that almost all a(n) satisfy the asymptotic formula a(n) = n (1+ 1/(3 log n)) + o(n/log n) as n -> oo and that the exceptional terms when the sequence is a prime or 3 times a prime p produce the spikes in the sequence. See the paper for a more precise statement of the conjecture. - _N. J. A. Sloane_, Mar 07 2015

A064414.name: Fix a > 0, b > 0, k > 0 and define G_1 = a, G_2 = b, G_k = G_(k-1) + G_(k-2); sequence gives numbers m such that there exists (a, b) where G_k is divisible by m.

A064415.name: a(1) = 0, a(n) = iter(n) if n is even, a(n) = iter(n)-1 if n is odd, where iter(n) = A003434(n) = smallest number of iterations of Euler totient function phi needed to reach 1.
formula: For all integers m >0 and n>0 a(m*n)=a(m)+a(n). The function a(n) is completely additive. The smallest integer q which satisfy the equation a(q)=n is 2^q, the greatest is 3^q. For all integers n>0, the counter image off n, a^-1(n) is finite.
a(1) = 0 and a(n) = A054725(n) for n>=2. - _Joerg Arndt_, Apr 08 2014, A-number corrected by _Antti Karttunen_, May 13 2020
a(1) = 0, a(2) = 1 and for n > 2, a(n) = sum(p | n, a(p-1)), where sum is over all primes p that divide n, with multiplicity. (Cf. A054725).
a(1) = 0, a(2) = 1 and a(p) = 1 + a((p-1)/2) if p is an odd prime and a(n*m) = a(n) + a(m) if m,n > 1. [From above formula, 1+ compensates for the "lost" 2]
a(n) = A007814(A309243(n)). [From _Rémy Sigrist_'s conjecture in the latter sequence. This reduces to a(n) = sum(p|n, a(p-1)) formula above, thus holds also]
If A209229(n) = 1 [when n is a power of 2], a(n) = A007814(n), otherwise a(n) = a(n-A052126(n)) = a(A171462(n)). [From the definition in the comments]

A064416.name: Number of integers q such that phiter(q)=n where phiter(n) = A064415(n).

A064417.name: a(1) = 1, a(2) = 2, a(3) = 3; for n >3 a(n) = smallest number not already used such that gcd(a(n), a(n-1)) >= 3.

A064418.name: a(1) = 1, a(2) = 2, a(3) = 3, a(4) = 4; for n > 4, a(n) = smallest number not already used such that gcd(a(n), a(n-1)) >= 4.

A064419.name: a(n) = n for n <= 5; for n > 5, a(n) = smallest number not already used such that gcd(a(n), a(n-1)) >= 5.

A064420.name: Numbers n such that A064413(n+1) = n. Probably complete.

A064421.name: Term at which n appears in A064413 (if it begins at 2).

A064422.name: Football league numbers: the possible point series for a league of n teams playing each other twice where for each match 3 points are awarded to the winning team and 1 to each in the case of a tie.

A064423.name: Position of n-th prime in A064413 (if it begins at 2).

A064425.name: Gaps between where primes occur in A064413.

A064428.name: Number of partitions of n with nonnegative crank.

A064429.name: a(n) = floor(n / 3) * 3 + sign(n mod 3) * (3 - n mod 3).
formula: a(n) = A001477(n) + A102283(n). - _Jaume Oliver Lafont_, Dec 05 2008
a(n) = a(n-1) + a(n-3) - a(n-4) for n > 3. - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Oct 06 2017

A064430.name: Product of the sizes of the conjugacy classes of the symmetric group S_n.

A064432.name: Least k such that k*10^n-9, k*10^n-7, k*10^n-3 and k*10^n-1 are all prime.

A064433.name: Number of iterations of A064455 to reach 2 (or 1 in the case of 1).

A064436.name: Number of switching functions of n or fewer variables which cannot be realized as threshold gates.

A064437.name: a(1)=1, a(n)=a(n-1)+3 if n is already in the sequence, a(n)=a(n-1)+2 otherwise.

A064438.name: Numbers which are divisible by the sum of their quaternary digits.

A064439.name: Numbers n such that sigma(n) - n - 1 = pi(n).

A064440.name: A048138(n) is a prime and sets a new record for such primes.

A064441.name: Increasing partial quotients of e^Pi - Pi^e (A063504).

A064442.name: Decimal expansion of number with continued fraction expansion 2, 3, 5, 7, 11, 13, 17, 19, ... = 2.3130367364335829063839516 ...
formula: Denoting the constant by c we have the related simple continued fraction expansions (prime(n) denotes the n-th prime number):

A064443.name: Numbers k such that usigma(k) is a square and sets a new record for such squares.

A064444.name: Numbers k such that pi(k) = sopf(k).

A064445.name: Numbers k such that sopf(k) - pi(k) = tau(k).

A064446.name: a(n) = gcd(n!, n^n, lcm(1, 2, ..., n)), or gcd(n^n, lcm(1, 2, ..., n)).
formula: a(n) = Product_{prime p | n} p^floor(log_p(n)). - _Robert Israel_, Oct 26 2015
a(n) = e^(Sum_{k=1..n} (floor(n^k/k) - floor((n^k - 1)/k))*Mangoldt(k)) where Mangoldt is the Mangoldt function. - _Anthony Browne_, Jun 16 2016

A064448.name: a(n) = gcd(n^n, EulerPhi(n^n)).
formula: If n = Product_j (p_j)^(e_j) is the prime factorization of n, then a(n) = Product_j p_j^(n e_j - 1) * gcd(Product_j p_j, Product_j (p_j-1)). - _Robert Israel_, Jan 18 2018

A064450.name: Sum of totients of binomial coefficients C(n,j), j=0..n.

A064451.name: LCM of totients of binomial coefficients C(n,j), j = 0..n.

A064452.name: Integers which are not primes or powers of primes such that for all j>i Phi(j)/j > Phi(i)/i.

A064453.name: Number of finite positive integer sequences b(1),...,b(k), with k <= n and b(1)*b(2)*...*b(k) <= n.

A064455.name: a(2n) = 3n, a(2n-1) = n.
formula: a(n) = n - A123684(n-1) for odd n.
a(n) = n + a(n-1) for even n.
a(n) = n + floor(n/2)*(-1)^(n mod 2). - _Bruno Berselli_, Dec 14 2015
a(n) = (n^2-3n+2) mod (2n-1) for n>2. - _Jim Singh_, Oct 31 2018

A064457.name: a(1) = 3; for n > 1, choose a(n) to be the smallest number such that a(n) > a(n-1) and (a(n)*a(n-1)+1) mod (a(n)+a(n-1)+1) = 0.

A064460.name: Number of distinct nonsquarefree entries in n-th row of Pascal's triangle.

A064461.name: First row of Pascal's triangle that has n distinct nonsquarefree entries, or -1 if no such row exists.

A064462.name: First row of Pascal's triangle that has n nonsquarefree entries, or -1 if no such row exists.

A064463.name: Numbers k such that A001414(k) is a square and sets a new record for squares.

A064464.name: Binary order (cf. A029837) of the number of parts if 3^n is partitioned into parts of size 2^n as far as possible and into parts of size 1^n (cf. A060692).

A064465.name: Numbers k such that A048138(k) = A034444(k).

A064466.name: a(0) = 6 and a(n) = Min { m > a(n-1) | both a(n-1) - p and m - p are prime for some prime p } for n > 0.

A064467.name: Primes in Pi: a(n) = first position in decimal expansion of Pi that matches the n-th prime, or 0 if there is no such position.

A064468.name: Positions of powers of 2 in A064413 (if it starts at 2).

A064473.name: Where the odd terms appear in A064413 (if it begins at 2).

A064475.name: Number of odd terms among first n terms of A064413 (if it begins at 2).
